## 8. Escalation Logic

After the Regulator produces its output, `main.py` enforces hard escalation thresholds regardless of what the model decided:

```python
ESCALATION_THRESHOLDS = {
    "regulator_confidence_min": 0.70,
    "farmer_deficit_pct_max":   30.0,
    "energy_shortage_critical": "critical",
    "market_stock_days_min":    14.0,
}

# Enforced in RegulatorAgent.analyze():
if payload.confidence_score < t["regulator_confidence_min"]:
    payload.escalate_to_human = True
    payload.escalation_reason = f"Confidence {payload.confidence_score:.2f} below threshold"

if band_room_state.farmer.deficit_pct > t["farmer_deficit_pct_max"]:
    payload.escalate_to_human = True
    payload.escalation_reason = f"Deficit {deficit}% exceeds threshold 30%"

if band_room_state.energy.shortage_alert == "critical":
    payload.escalate_to_human = True
    payload.escalation_reason = "Critical energy shortage — cascading food risk"

if band_room_state.market.stock_level_days < t["market_stock_days_min"]:
    payload.escalate_to_human = True
    payload.escalation_reason = f"Stock {days}d below critical 14d"
```

The model's confidence score is advisory. The threshold enforcement is unconditional Python code.

